---
import ToolLayout from '../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';
import MediaConverter from '../components/MediaConverter.astro';
---

<ToolLayout slug="m4a-to-mp3">
  <MediaConverter slug="m4a-to-mp3" />

  <div slot="about" class="flex flex-col gap-6 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink-subtle">
    <p>
      This free M4A to MP3 converter turns Apple M4A and AAC audio — including iPhone voice memos, Apple Music downloads, and audiobook tracks — into MP3 files that play on any device, car stereo, or media player. There is no file-size limit.
    </p>

    <div>
      <span class="eyebrow text-primary-hover">What you can control</span>
      <ul class="mt-3 flex flex-col gap-2">
        <li><span class="text-ink">Bitrate &amp; quality</span> — variable-bitrate presets (V0, V2, V4) for the best size-to-quality balance, or fixed CBR from 320 kbps down to 64 kbps for voice.</li>
        <li><span class="text-ink">Sample rate &amp; channels</span> — keep the original, resample to 48/44.1/32/16/8 kHz, and fold to mono or keep stereo.</li>
        <li><span class="text-ink">Loudness normalization</span> — EBU R128 normalize evens out quiet and loud files to a consistent level, something most online converters skip.</li>
        <li><span class="text-ink">Trim &amp; fade</span> — set start/end points and add fade-in or fade-out without a separate editor.</li>
        <li><span class="text-ink">Batch conversion</span> — drop in multiple M4A files, convert them with the same settings, preview each result inline, and download them individually or all at once as a ZIP.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div>
      <span class="eyebrow text-primary-hover">FAQ</span>
      <div class="mt-3 flex flex-col gap-4">
        <div>
          <p class="text-ink">Will I lose quality converting M4A to MP3?</p>
          <p>Both formats are lossy, so re-encoding discards a little detail. Choosing V0 or 320 kbps keeps the result transparent for almost all listening. For spoken-word audio like voice memos, 96 or 64 kbps mono produces much smaller files with no noticeable loss.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-ink">Does it work with iPhone voice memos and AAC files?</p>
          <p>Yes. Voice-memo recordings, AAC audio, and M4A files exported from Apple Music or QuickTime are all accepted and converted to standard MP3.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-ink">Can I convert several files at once?</p>
          <p>Yes. Add as many files as you like, apply one set of settings to the whole queue, and grab everything as a single ZIP when it finishes.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</ToolLayout>
